 17%|█▋        | 1/6 [00:00<00:00,  8.74it/s]Question: What is the CAP theorem?
Example answer: The CAP theorem states that a distributed data store can only
  simultaneously provide two of the three following guarantees:
  Consistency (every read receives the most recent write),
  Availability (every request receives a response), and Partition
  tolerance (the system continues to operate despite network
  partitions). This means distributed systems must trade off one of
  these properties.
Predicted answer: The CAP theorem, proposed by Eric Brewer, asserts that a distributed
  data store cannot simultaneously achieve all three of the following
  guarantees: Consistency (every read receives the most recent write
  or an error), Availability (every request receives a response
  without errors, but not necessarily the most recent write), and
  Partition tolerance (the system continues to operate despite network
  failures). In the case of a network partition, a choice must be made
  between maintaining consistency or availability.
Rationale: The recall score is set at 1.0 because the prediction answer fully
  encompasses the critical elements provided in the example answer
  related to the CAP theorem. It mentions all three components
  (Consistency, Availability, Partition tolerance), the impossibility
  of simultaneously achieving all three, and the necessary trade-offs
  in distributed systems, thereby matching the depth of example
  answer.
Score: 1.0

